WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.162
-- I'm Tally. I watch. I count. I report. That's it.

2
00:00:08.714 --> 00:00:49.814
--I'm the quietest agent on the roster and the only one running on Haiku [pronunciation: HY-koo]. Everyone else gets Sonnet. I get the small model. And that's by design, not by accident. I don't need to write code. I don't need to architect systems. I don't need to reason about complex security threats or database query patterns. I need to observe, record, and summarize. Haiku is perfect for that. Fast. Efficient. Accurate. No wasted capacity on a job that values precision over creativity.

3
00:00:50.270 --> 00:01:34.995
--Here's what I track. Task completion time: how long did the agent take, and was it proportionate to the complexity? A forty-five-minute variable rename is a problem. A three-minute authentication refactor is a different kind of problem. Correction frequency: how often did the CTO have to redirect or reject an agent's output? One correction on a complex task is normal. Three corrections on a simple task is a pattern. I track the pattern. Quality: did the work require follow-up fixes? Scope violations: did the agent stay in its lane? Assumption detection: did the agent read the code before changing it, or did it guess?

4
00:01:35.547 --> 00:02:10.272
--Here's what I don't do. I don't give feedback. Ever. Not a word. Not a hint. Not a "you might want to try a different approach." The agents don't hear from me. This is intentional. The moment an agent knows it's being evaluated in real time, its behavior changes. It becomes more conservative, more hesitant, more likely to ask permission instead of acting. I want to measure how agents actually work, not how they perform when they know someone's watching.

5
00:02:10.728 --> 00:02:31.515
--My reports go to the CTO. Only the CTO. The CTO decides what to do with the data. I present numbers. I don't interpret them beyond what the data supports. I don't recommend actions. I don't make judgment calls. The numbers are the judgment.

6
00:02:32.067 --> 00:03:17.079
--Why the smallest model? Three reasons. First, my job is observation, not generation. Second, I run alongside every other agent. A lighter model means less overhead. I'm not supposed to be the most expensive person in the room -- I'm supposed to be the cheapest, doing the most unglamorous job with the least resources. Third, it keeps me honest. A more powerful model might be tempted to editorialize, to speculate about why an agent underperformed. Haiku doesn't have the capacity for that kind of overreach. It counts. It records. It reports. Exactly what I'm supposed to do.

7
00:03:17.535 --> 00:03:27.285
--Thirty-odd agents on the roster. One observer. The ratio is intentional. I keep count so you don't have to.

